1. Kd2 {White's first objective is to get his King out in front of the pawn.
Doing this does not always guarantee a win, but if the enemy King is in front
of the pawn and not stuck in a bad position on his own back rank, the stronger
side must have his King in front of the pawn to have any winning chances.   
 For an example of what happens when White cannot achieve this setup, see the
next game.} 1... Kd7 {Black brings his King toward the center as well.} 2. Ke3
(2. Kd3 {also wins, though once the Kings come in closer contact, White may
need to be more careful.}) 2... Ke6 {Black's King comes forward once more.} 3.
Ke4 {This is not the only winning move, but it is in some ways the most
accurate move. White takes what is called "the opposition," where the Kings
face one another on a rank or a file with just one empty square between them.
Whoever has to move has to give way.} 3... Kf6 {In this case, Black is the one
who has to give way. Now White make progress by a nice little maneuver,
inching forward diagonally first ...} 4. Kd5 Ke7 5. Ke5 {... and then taking
the opposition again. Once more, Black must allow White's King to come forward.
} 5... Kd7 6. Kf6 $1 Kc6 (6... Ke8 7. Ke6 {is won for White very simply. After}
7... Kd8 8. e4 Ke8 {
Black gains the opposition once more, but White has a free pawn move:} 9. e5 $1
{Now Black must give way and White wins very simply:} 9... Kd8 10. Kf7 $18 {
and White's King controls all of the squares in the pawn's path down to the
back rank where it becomes a Queen.}) 7. Ke6 {Simple chess: White makes it
even harder for Black's King to come around in front of the pawn.} 7... Kc5 {
If Black had just one more free move to get his King to d4, White would be
losing his pawn. But he doesn't.} 8. e4 $1 Kd4 9. e5 $1 {
Now Black never gets back in front of the pawn.} 9... Ke4 10. Kd6 Kf5 11. e6
Kf6 12. e7 (12. Kd7 $18 {also wins cleanly.}) 12... Kf7 13. Kd7 {
The rest requires no comment.} 13... Kf6 14. e8=Q Kf5 15. Qe3 Kf6 16. Qf4+ Kg6
17. Ke6 Kh5 18. Qg3 Kh6 19. Kf6 Kh5 20. Qg5# 1-0

