1. Kd2 {In this position, the pawn is a bit further advanced. This means that
White has greater difficulty getting his King in front of the pawn. In fact,
in this one case, the King can get in front of the pawn only for a price ...}
1... Kd7 2. Kd3 Ke7 $1 {This move looks mysterious until you remember the
concept of taking the opposition. Black does not know what square White will
come up to, d4 or e4, and he must be prepared to meet each of these by taking
the opposition. So he waits, one rank back, forcing White to show his hand.} 3.
Ke4 (3. Kd4 Kd6 $1) (3. Kc4 Ke6 $1 {takes the "diagonal opposition." You
should verify for yourself that White cannot force a win now. Black's
immediate plan is to play Ke5-e4, camping in front of the pawn. White can stop
that, but then Black can take the (direct) opposition, e.g.} 4. Kd4 Kd6 5. Ke4
Ke6 6. Kf4 Kf6 7. Ke4 Ke6 {and without moving the pawn forward, White cannot
make any progress. So play transposes into the main line, where Black keeps
the draw with precise play.}) 3... Ke6 $1 4. Kd4 Kd6 $1 5. e4 Ke6 $1 6. e5 {
Black's King stands immediately in front of the pawn, but it is his move and
he has to give way. He therefore chooses the one square where it is impossible,
by the rules of chess, for White to take the opposition -- because White's own
pawn is on the square his King would need.} 6... Ke7 {"Drop straight back when
you can't stay on the blockade square." That is the rule to remember. If you
do this, you will always draw this endgame.} 7. Kd5 Kd7 $1 {
Of course: Black takes the opposition.} 8. e6+ Ke7 {Blockade -- not the only
drawing move, but the best one  because it develops good habits for positions
where doing this is critical.} 9. Ke5 Ke8 $1 {Drop straight back! Here, this
move is absolutely critical -- going to either side would lose immediately.} (
9... Kd8 $4 10. Kd6 Ke8 11. e7 Kf7 12. Kd7 {and White wins.}) 10. Kd6 Kd8 $1 {
Take the opposition!} 11. e7+ Ke8 $1 {
Blockade! Now White has only one move that does not lose his pawn, but ...} 12.
Ke6 {... stalemate.} 1/2-1/2

